The paper deals with dynamic data structures for storing and manipulating geometric objects, specifically quadtrees in constant dimensions. This makes it likely to belong to the computational geometry (cs.CG) and data structures (cs.DS) sub-categories. The paper also deals with compression and alignment of quadtree components, which falls under the data management (cs.DM) sub-category. The use of quadtrees in various computational geometry problems suggests that it could also belong to the systems and control (cs.SY) sub-category. Finally, the paper's focus on worst-case constant time updates suggests that it could be relevant to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category, which often deals with efficient algorithms and data structures.
